{"id":"2010.06873","submitter":"Christian Deppe","authors":"Holger Boche and Christian Deppe","title":"Computability of the Zero-Error Capacity of Noisy Channels","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.IT math.IT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Zero-error capacity plays an important role in a whole range of operational\ntasks, in addition to the fact that it is necessary for practical applications.\nDue to the importance of zero-error capacity, it is necessary to investigate\nits algorithmic computability, as there has been no known closed formula for\nthe zero-error capacity until now. We show that the zero-error capacity of\nnoisy channels is not Banach-Mazur computable and therefore not Borel-Turing\ncomputable. We also investigate the relationship between the zero-error\ncapacity of discrete memoryless channels, the Shannon capacity of graphs, and\nAhlswede's characterization of the zero-error-capacity of noisy channels with\nrespect to the maximum error capacity of 0-1-arbitrarily varying channels. We\nwill show that important questions regarding semi-decidability are equivalent\nfor all three capacities. So far, the Borel-Turing computability of the Shannon\ncapacity of graphs is completely open. This is why the coupling with\nsemi-decidability is interesting.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 14 Oct 2020 08:30:08 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 19 May 2021 07:32:04 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-05-20"}
