{"id":"2010.06904","submitter":"Jirawat Saiphet","authors":"Jirawat Saiphet, Sujin Suwanna, Andr\\'e R. R. Carvalho, Areeya\n  Chantasri","title":"Time-delayed quantum feedback and incomplete decoherence suppression\n  with no-knowledge measurement","comments":"10 pages and 5 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 103, 022208 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.103.022208","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The no-knowledge quantum feedback was proposed by Szigeti et al., Phys. Rev.\nLett. 113, 020407 (2014), as a measurement-based feedback protocol for\ndecoherence suppression for an open quantum system. By continuously measuring\nenvironmental noises and feeding back controls on the system, the protocol can\ncompletely reverse the measurement backaction and therefore suppress the\nsystem's decoherence. However, the complete decoherence cancellation was shown\nonly for the instantaneous feedback, which is impractical in real experiments.\nTherefore, in this work, we generalize the original work and investigate how\nthe decoherence suppression can be degraded with unavoidable delay times, by\nanalyzing non-Markovian average dynamics. We present analytical expressions for\nthe average dynamics and numerically analyze the effects of the delayed\nfeedback for a coherently driven two-level system, coupled to a bosonic bath\nvia a Hermitian coupling operator. We also find that, when the qubit's unitary\ndynamics does not commute with the measurement and feedback controls, the\ndecoherence rate can be either suppressed or amplified, depending on the delay\ntime.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 14 Oct 2020 09:32:24 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 16 Feb 2021 06:43:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-02-17"}
